      <para id="import-auto-id1290839">Why do most objects tend to contain nearly equal numbers of positive and negative charges?</para>
      </problem></exercise>
      </section>
      <section id="fs-id1542554" type="problems-exercises" class="problems-exercises"><title>Problems &amp; Exercises</title>
          <exercise id="fs-id2878870" type="problem-exercises"><problem id="fs-id1925134">        <para id="import-auto-id2288523">Common static electricity involves charges ranging from nanocoulombs to microcoulombs. (a) How many electrons are needed to form a charge of <m:math><m:mrow><m:mn>–2.00</m:mn><m:mspace width="0.25em"/><m:mtext>nC</m:mtext></m:mrow></m:math> (b) How many electrons must be removed from a neutral object to leave a net charge of <m:math><m:mrow><m:mn>0.500</m:mn><m:mspace width="0.25em"/><m:mi>µ</m:mi><m:mtext>C</m:mtext></m:mrow></m:math>?</para></problem>
<solution id="fs-id1752095">
      <para id="import-auto-id1973840">(a) <m:math><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mn>1.25</m:mn><m:mrow><m:mo stretchy="false">×</m:mo><m:msup><m:mtext>10</m:mtext><m:mrow><m:mtext>10</m:mtext></m:mrow></m:msup></m:mrow></m:mrow></m:mrow></m:mrow></m:math></para><para id="import-auto-id1534500">(b) <m:math><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mn>3.13</m:mn><m:mrow><m:mo stretchy="false">×</m:mo><m:msup><m:mtext>10</m:mtext><m:mrow><m:mtext>12</m:mtext></m:mrow></m:msup></m:mrow></m:mrow></m:mrow></m:mrow></m:math></para></solution>
      </exercise>
          <exercise id="fs-id1893695" type="problem-exercises"><problem id="fs-id1532740">        <para id="import-auto-id2216258">If <m:math><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mn>1</m:mn><m:mtext>.</m:mtext><m:mrow><m:mtext>80</m:mtext><m:mo stretchy="false">×</m:mo><m:msup><m:mtext>10</m:mtext><m:mrow><m:mtext>20</m:mtext></m:mrow></m:msup></m:mrow></m:mrow></m:mrow></m:mrow></m:math> electrons move through a pocket calculator during a full day’s operation, how many coulombs of charge moved through it?</para>
      </problem></exercise>
          <exercise id="fs-id1969597" type="problem-exercises"><problem id="fs-id1456604">        <para id="import-auto-id1607838">To start a car engine, the car battery moves <m:math><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mn>3</m:mn><m:mtext>.</m:mtext><m:mrow><m:mtext>75</m:mtext><m:mo stretchy="false">×</m:mo><m:msup><m:mtext>10</m:mtext><m:mrow><m:mtext>21</m:mtext></m:mrow></m:msup></m:mrow></m:mrow></m:mrow></m:mrow></m:math> electrons through the starter motor. How many coulombs of charge were moved?</para>
      </problem>
<solution id="fs-id2283981">
      <para id="import-auto-id1769282">-600 C</para>
      </solution>
      </exercise>
          <exercise id="fs-id2272902" type="problem-exercises"><problem id="fs-id911073">        <para id="import-auto-id1985653">A certain lightning bolt moves 40.0 C of charge. How many fundamental units of charge <m:math>
      
        <m:mrow>

            <m:mrow>
              <m:mrow>
                <m:mrow>
                  <m:mrow>
                    <m:mo stretchy="false">∣</m:mo>
                    <m:msub>
                      <m:mi>q</m:mi>

